00:00:24.070 --> 00:00:25.790
GARY GENSLER:
Today's a little bit

00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:31.010
of a discussion about clearing
and settlement systems.

00:00:31.010 --> 00:00:32.720
Maybe you feel you've
heard everything

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:35.270
you needed from Jeff
Sprecher when he was asked

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:37.340
a question when he was with us.

00:00:37.340 --> 00:00:39.180
Jeff runs some of
the largest clearing

00:00:39.180 --> 00:00:42.860
houses in the world at
Intercontinental Exchange

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:47.660
not only because he started
in the energy business,

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:51.650
but he has big credit default
swap clearing houses and energy

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:53.630
clearing houses and the like.

00:00:53.630 --> 00:00:57.740
And he said, well, I don't know
about blockchain technology

00:00:57.740 --> 00:00:58.910
for clearing and settling.

00:00:58.910 --> 00:01:02.180
But I'm going to try this
Bitcoin project that you all

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:03.800
know about and he talked about.

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:06.277
But today we're going
to try to dig into,

00:01:06.277 --> 00:01:08.360
well, maybe there's something
there, because there

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:10.010
are projects going on.

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:11.380
And why are there projects?

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:16.580
They're mostly permissioned
and not permissionless systems.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:20.160
But I think there's
something there.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:22.560
This will be one of
the more optimistic--

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:27.120
if you're judging how often
I get to the maximal side,

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:29.540
I think there is probably
something there, at least

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:32.420
for permissioned blockchain
projects in the clearing

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:34.940
and settling.

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:38.270
I'm going to-- we'll, of
course, go through the readings.

00:01:38.270 --> 00:01:41.060
And these are the sort of
topics we'll go through.

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:43.010
Clearing and settling services--

00:01:43.010 --> 00:01:47.330
I'm going to try to set this
stage as to what this is.

00:01:47.330 --> 00:01:50.210
Frankly, when I was on
Wall Street for 18 years,

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:53.210
I couldn't really define
what clearing and settling.

00:01:53.210 --> 00:01:53.960
Sorry, Ross.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:56.950
You thought I could define
it when I was on Wall Street?

00:01:56.950 --> 00:01:57.790
What's that?

00:01:57.790 --> 00:01:59.570
AUDIENCE: I just strictly know
someone else can't either.

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:00.362
GARY GENSLER: Yeah.

00:02:00.362 --> 00:02:00.872
Yeah.

00:02:00.872 --> 00:02:03.080
Well, when you're in the
merger and acquisition area,

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:04.910
you usually don't
think about what

00:02:04.910 --> 00:02:07.657
it means to clear
something and to settle it.

00:02:07.657 --> 00:02:09.199
And frankly, even
usually when you're

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:12.110
on the trading floor, that's
something somebody else

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:14.840
takes care of.

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:16.580
Just the nature of--

00:02:16.580 --> 00:02:20.470
how many people have worked
on trading floors here?

00:02:20.470 --> 00:02:20.970
All right.

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:23.850
So I'm going to have seven
or eight of you start.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:26.310
And you're on notice now.

00:02:26.310 --> 00:02:30.490
In about eight to 10 minutes,
you're going to help.

00:02:30.490 --> 00:02:34.147
You might prove what I just said
to Ross, that you can't define

00:02:34.147 --> 00:02:36.480
what clearing and settling
is because somebody else took

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:37.100
care of it.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:38.400
But we'll see.

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.140
We'll see.

00:02:40.140 --> 00:02:42.450
And then we'll talk about
blockchain technology

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:46.060
applicability, some of the
projects that are going on,

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:48.330
and then move over to this.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:51.135
There was a reading from
the International Swaps

00:02:51.135 --> 00:02:54.600
and Derivatives
Association, ISDA,

00:02:54.600 --> 00:03:00.090
what they're doing around
smart contracts in this space.

00:03:00.090 --> 00:03:02.613
But what I want to do
first is a little bit

00:03:02.613 --> 00:03:04.530
of talking about final
projects, because we're

00:03:04.530 --> 00:03:06.120
at that time of the year.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:09.420
And this is to help.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:12.990
Then I'm going to go through
eight or nine questions.

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:17.280
If you haven't already
thought through your projects,

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:18.690
these are eight
or nine questions

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:22.740
that I would think you'd
want to think about,

00:03:22.740 --> 00:03:24.810
which is another way of
saying it will probably

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:28.260
enhance your performance.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:31.530
What else can I say?

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:34.260
And number one-- and it's
a little, small print.

00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:34.890
I'm sorry.

00:03:34.890 --> 00:03:37.110
Or no, it's not too bad--

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:41.340
is what's the value creation
proposition, or pain point,

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:42.100
if you wish.

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:44.070
So are you creating value?

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:45.428
Are you solving a pain point?

00:03:45.428 --> 00:03:47.220
Or as Jeff Sprecher
would say, what are you

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:51.880
doing that's going to make
something cheaper, faster,

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:53.610
better?

00:03:53.610 --> 00:03:55.470
What's the value proposition?

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:56.880
Whatever space.

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:00.320
There's two or three groups
that are doing trade finance.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:02.220
There's one or two
doing payments.

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:06.990
There's some group
doing commercial--

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:11.470
I mean, consumer credit
rating or so forth.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:12.942
There's a wide variety.

00:04:12.942 --> 00:04:14.400
There's one or two
groups that have

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:18.209
come to see me that are doing
things outside of finance.

00:04:18.209 --> 00:04:22.660
But regardless, what's
the value proposition?

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.170
What pain points
are you addressing?

00:04:25.170 --> 00:04:26.900
Or as Jeff would say,
what are you going

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:30.000
to do better, faster, cheaper?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.960
If you can't answer
that threshold question,

00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:35.820
shake it loose.

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:37.350
Kick it around.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:42.270
Or move on to a different
use case, frankly.

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:43.950
Secondly, [INAUDIBLE]
you get into,

00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:46.170
like, what is this
blockchain technology?

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:50.610
What transactions or data
is going to be recorded?

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:52.650
Because this is
fundamentally, ultimately,

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:57.130
a database technology, even
the permissionless systems.

00:04:57.130 --> 00:05:00.210
And you'll see a later
question is why this versus

00:05:00.210 --> 00:05:01.860
traditional database system?

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:03.810
But what transactions,
what data--

00:05:03.810 --> 00:05:05.880
whether it's health
care records,

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:10.260
whether it's consumer
credit data, supply chain,

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:13.350
moving a piece of property
along a supply chain,

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:16.230
but what is the actual data
and transactions that you're

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:17.550
recording?

00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:19.820
Questions?

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:23.510
What multiple stakeholders
need to write and read access

00:05:23.510 --> 00:05:24.590
to the ledgers?

00:05:24.590 --> 00:05:26.390
And I underline
the word multiple.

00:05:26.390 --> 00:05:30.080
Because really, when you think
about the value proposition

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:35.950
of blockchain technology,
it's about immutable records,

00:05:35.950 --> 00:05:38.180
or so-called immutable records.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:41.630
That's verifiable,
immutable records

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:45.090
amongst multiple parties.

00:05:45.090 --> 00:05:46.560
And it cost extra money.

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:49.710
Everything we've been studying
about in this semester

00:05:49.710 --> 00:05:51.330
is about there's
more complexity.

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:55.290
There's more cost, in some
way, of this decentralized,

00:05:55.290 --> 00:06:00.300
even permissioned systems,
decentralized system.

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:02.100
But you get something for it.

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:06.100
You get some verification
of transactions, of data,

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:08.070
of mutability.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:10.800
But you also have
to have some logic

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:12.420
that there's
multiple parties that

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:15.600
need to both write and read.

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:19.390
A distributed database
that just does read only--

00:06:19.390 --> 00:06:23.290
I can read my Bank of
America bank account.

00:06:23.290 --> 00:06:26.230
I can see what's in
that sort of ledger.

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:28.180
It doesn't have to
be on a blockchain.

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:31.720
So multiple parties writing,
why is that important?

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:36.700
Forming consensus,
in this circumstance.

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:39.610
Which specific cost of
verification or networking

00:06:39.610 --> 00:06:40.510
are you lowering?

00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:43.780
We talked about a lot of
the verification costs,

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:47.350
whether it's privacy,
censorship resistance,

00:06:47.350 --> 00:06:49.258
whether it's some direct cost.

00:06:49.258 --> 00:06:50.800
Maybe you're going
right at something

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:53.590
that's got a bunch of
economic rents in it.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:55.750
So there was a series
of verification costs

00:06:55.750 --> 00:06:57.460
we talked about.

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:00.490
What networking costs
are you trying to reduce?

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:06.430
There's probably been
something in the order

00:07:06.430 --> 00:07:11.470
of 4,000 or 5,000 white
papers, many that you can find.

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:13.062
You can't find all of them.

00:07:13.062 --> 00:07:14.770
But if you're going
at something that you

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:16.660
think a white paper
has been written about

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:19.240
or a blockchain company
has been started on,

00:07:19.240 --> 00:07:22.080
figure out what the
competition is doing.

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:23.920
And for the two groups,
and it may be more,

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:26.620
that are doing something around
trade, finance, and supply

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:30.730
chain, you know there's a
bunch of stuff you can read.

00:07:30.730 --> 00:07:32.260
We'll be studying
it next Tuesday.

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:32.973
Alin?

00:07:32.973 --> 00:07:35.390
AUDIENCE: Can you give us an
example of a networking cost?

00:07:35.390 --> 00:07:36.670
I'm not sure what that is.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:40.690
GARY GENSLER: So
networking cost is often

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:44.170
why people are using
a native token.

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:50.730
But networking costs are
how to jumpstart a network.

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:54.270
Uber jumpstarted a
network, in a sense,

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:55.850
without blockchain technology.

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:57.750
But an example of
networking costs

00:07:57.750 --> 00:08:00.200
are if you walked
out of the airport

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:04.790
and you didn't think any drivers
are using this application,

00:08:04.790 --> 00:08:08.480
then you wouldn't be terribly
interested in using it.

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:09.720
So--

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.860
AUDIENCE: But who
incurs the cost?

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:16.760
GARY GENSLER: Often the cost
of building a network can

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:19.860
be a tremendous startup cost.

00:08:19.860 --> 00:08:22.052
So how to start a
network often is

00:08:22.052 --> 00:08:23.760
you go to a bunch of
venture capitalists.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.010
You raise money.

00:08:25.010 --> 00:08:26.600
You advertise.

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:29.430
And you try to get participants.

00:08:29.430 --> 00:08:32.900
And one of the challenges
of health care records--

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:35.990
we don't have our health
care experts in here today.

00:08:39.825 --> 00:08:40.700
I was looking around.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:44.240
We have two students from
Harvard's public policy

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:48.170
school doing graduate work
and sometimes join us.

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:50.460
But health care
records, for instance,

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:54.650
there's some really interesting
blockchain technology

00:08:54.650 --> 00:08:56.070
solutions.

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:57.920
But the networking
challenge is how do you

00:08:57.920 --> 00:09:02.500
get a bunch of medical
providers, hospitals, doctors,

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:06.350
and users to actually
join the network.

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:09.230
So that would be an
example of network cost

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:11.395
is basically adoption often.

00:09:11.395 --> 00:09:12.020
Does that help?

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:12.645
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:17.730
GARY GENSLER: What are
the competitors doing?

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:19.380
I'm not looking for plagiarism.

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:23.580
But if you're in a space,
payments or supply chain

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:26.130
or consumer credit
or some others,

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:29.010
where there's three or six
or 10 white papers out there

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:31.680
and maybe somebody has
even raised 20 million

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:37.050
or a couple million in an ICO,
then it would be interesting.

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:38.730
You should feel free
to look at those.

00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:40.470
And maybe you'll
be informed by it.

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:42.220
And you'll say, yeah,
I'm doing it better.

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:44.550
Or they've got it poorly here.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:47.070
Or their project's in Estonia.

00:09:47.070 --> 00:09:50.730
And I'm going to do a
digital ID project in the US.

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:54.240
And our regulatory system
is different than Estonia.

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:58.060
But I wouldn't be bashful about
looking at the competition.

00:09:58.060 --> 00:09:59.400
In fact, I would say that's--

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:00.400
we're a business school.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.130
You always look at
the competition.

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:05.040
And you see if you can do
either what they're doing better

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:07.140
or what they're doing
in a different geography

00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:09.500
or in a little bit
different market.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.750
Back to how Alin likes
to define things,

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:14.660
I've not used the term
blockchain technology yet

00:10:14.660 --> 00:10:17.120
on this slide, have I?

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:22.940
But why are append-only logs
at multiple party consensus

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:25.780
the best solution?

00:10:25.780 --> 00:10:27.730
Which kind of goes
back to why not just

00:10:27.730 --> 00:10:28.960
a traditional database.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:34.390
But why append-only,
timestamped, verifiable logs?

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:37.420
They're connected by
cryptographic hash functions.

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:39.790
But why have these logs?

00:10:39.790 --> 00:10:41.770
And why have multiple
parties in essence

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:46.665
form a consensus about
the state of the ledger?

00:10:46.665 --> 00:10:47.307
Alin?

00:10:47.307 --> 00:10:47.890
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:10:47.890 --> 00:10:51.590
I have a question about the
timestamped, apend-only logs.

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:54.420
Is that only relevant
in blockchain,

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.210
that traditional
databases do not

00:10:56.210 --> 00:11:01.740
have these kinds of features,
timestamp and append-only logs?

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:04.740
GARY GENSLER: They
can have time--

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:08.690
timestamps in essence.

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:11.130
In essence, it's innovation
of the early '90s.

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.070
And then Satoshi
Nakamoto grabbed it.

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:16.520
It was the concept that
you take a block of data

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:20.120
and you connect it to the next
block with a cryptographic hash

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:20.862
function.

00:11:20.862 --> 00:11:22.820
And once you've done
that, then it's committed.

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:26.050
You can't amend
anything that's before

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:29.460
because it's a unique hash.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:33.880
And traditional databases did
not have similar commitment

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:34.380
schemes.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:36.360
They do have other
commitments schemes, but not

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:39.720
this commitment scheme of
taking a block of data,

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:44.700
having the hash function,
which then means never shall

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:48.520
you amend what came before.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:49.960
That's how I understand it.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:53.295
Did you have a different view
on traditional databases?

00:11:53.295 --> 00:11:54.670
AUDIENCE: Well,
I guess this gets

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:56.620
to the root of the question.

00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:59.510
Is there something new
about blockchain technology?

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:02.050
In my opinion, there
isn't, actually.

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:06.140
20 years ago, we knew how to
make a traditional database

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:09.380
and make it full of power and
make it a census protocol,

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:12.497
or what people nowadays like to
call a permissioned blockchain.

00:12:12.497 --> 00:12:13.580
So we knew how to do that.

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:15.372
And that would give
you an append-only log.

00:12:15.372 --> 00:12:18.820
It's nothing exceptional.

00:12:21.808 --> 00:12:22.600
GARY GENSLER: Yeah.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:26.800
So there are debates as to
where is the border and boundary

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:28.420
between a permissioned
blockchain

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:31.190
and a traditional database.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:35.210
But I've chosen to, at
least for this class,

00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:39.890
a hyperledger fabric, we'll
call that a blockchain project.

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:43.970
But recognize there are some
who would say, well, that's--

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:48.610
unless you have a native token,
it's not really blockchain.

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:49.275
Eric.

00:12:49.275 --> 00:12:56.330
AUDIENCE: --one could call point
recent days that the trust is

00:12:56.330 --> 00:13:00.760
the key attribute that's not
the factor in this equation,

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:04.290
because you can get a multiple--

