it's called delivery
versus payment, or DVP.

00:25:16.310 --> 00:25:21.490
It's just a final change
of data record on a ledger.

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:22.630
In the old days--

00:25:22.630 --> 00:25:25.010
I'm talking about
before I was doing it.

00:25:25.010 --> 00:25:27.970
But 40 years to
hundreds of years

00:25:27.970 --> 00:25:30.240
ago, it was
physically delivering

00:25:30.240 --> 00:25:34.840
a physical piece of paper which
was a equity security or a bond

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:36.100
security.

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:39.850
But it all got dematerialized
starting in the 1970s.

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:41.950
And by the 1990s,
it was pretty much--

00:25:41.950 --> 00:25:44.260
in this country and the UK--

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:48.400
it was pretty much
dematerialized securities,

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:52.960
that everything's digitized now
in the equity markets in nearly

00:25:52.960 --> 00:25:56.290
every country that
you're all from and maybe

00:25:56.290 --> 00:25:59.200
with some small exceptions.

00:25:59.200 --> 00:26:03.240
So execution is I buy,
you sell, volume price.

00:26:03.240 --> 00:26:06.760
We've legally agreed
to something verbally.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:10.810
And billions of dollars
can trade on the phone

00:26:10.810 --> 00:26:13.330
or in the computer.

00:26:13.330 --> 00:26:14.650
Legally, it's executed.

00:26:14.650 --> 00:26:17.620
Clearing is trying to make
sure that you actually

00:26:17.620 --> 00:26:20.780
have the securities, and
I actually have the cash.

00:26:20.780 --> 00:26:21.670
We do some netting.

00:26:21.670 --> 00:26:23.320
We authenticate.

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:26.680
And settlement is actually
moving the data on the ledgers.

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:29.020
Three steps.

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:30.460
This is the benefit of netting.

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:32.750
It was just one chart that
I could find somewhere.

00:26:32.750 --> 00:26:34.690
It's actually the
Australian Stock Exchange

00:26:34.690 --> 00:26:37.540
had it on their website.

00:26:37.540 --> 00:26:40.430
But if you have multi-parties
in the transaction,

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:42.400
which was on the
left hand side--

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:45.460
and these are just arrows of
all the different transactions

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:48.850
that could occur in
one little example--

00:26:48.850 --> 00:26:56.310
and instead you interpose
a central intermediary,

00:26:56.310 --> 00:26:58.840
you can do a lot of netting.

00:26:58.840 --> 00:27:01.270
And look at participant
C. Participant C

00:27:01.270 --> 00:27:05.890
only has an exposure of
selling 35 of whatever they're

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:10.930
selling, some stock, versus
all these other transactions.

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:14.610
And this is a very simple case.

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:20.940
But if you have 20 or a hundred
clearing members that are all

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:24.300
big brokerage houses and
they're doing thousands or even

00:27:24.300 --> 00:27:28.550
hundreds of thousands
of trades a day,

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:32.690
you have an awful
lot of transactions.

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:35.750
And the gross transactions
versus the net

00:27:35.750 --> 00:27:37.560
is quite a difference.

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:41.660
That netting can bring down
numbers 90 plus percent

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:45.410
or maybe even 99% or more.

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:47.780
So central intermediaries--

00:27:47.780 --> 00:27:51.060
I know this goes against Satoshi
Nakamoto's whole concept--

00:27:51.060 --> 00:27:57.370
but central intermediaries came
about in the securities market

00:27:57.370 --> 00:27:58.580
for a bunch of reasons.

00:27:58.580 --> 00:28:03.890
But one of the biggest
ones was netting.

00:28:03.890 --> 00:28:06.140
Brotish?

00:28:06.140 --> 00:28:07.990
And it's a really
important concept

00:28:07.990 --> 00:28:09.640
in the back office
of Wall Street.

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:11.473
AUDIENCE: I'm not
familiar with the concept.

00:28:11.473 --> 00:28:12.370
So [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:12.370 --> 00:28:13.540
GARY GENSLER: You're
saying you're familiar?

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:15.000
AUDIENCE: I'm not familiar
with this concept,

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:16.460
so a clarification question.

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:17.657
GARY GENSLER: Please.

00:28:17.657 --> 00:28:19.240
AUDIENCE: When we
do netting, it seems

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:21.250
that we are losing
a lot of information

00:28:21.250 --> 00:28:22.630
here from the
gross transactions.

00:28:22.630 --> 00:28:23.680
So is it--

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:24.100
GARY GENSLER: That's right.

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:25.990
AUDIENCE: --just the
transfer of the asset

00:28:25.990 --> 00:28:27.940
is done through the
netting, but the records

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:30.040
of all the gross
transactions are still there

00:28:30.040 --> 00:28:31.450
with the central intermediaries?

00:28:31.450 --> 00:28:32.825
GARY GENSLER: Very
good question.

00:28:32.825 --> 00:28:35.230
So are we losing information?

00:28:35.230 --> 00:28:41.110
Or are we just lessening the
lines of counterparty risk

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:42.400
in the transactions?

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:44.290
And the answer is,
if done properly,

00:28:44.290 --> 00:28:48.880
you still keep the
information of all of these.

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:53.880
And in the real world, this
is just eight transactions.

00:28:53.880 --> 00:28:55.910
It's netted down to four.

00:28:55.910 --> 00:28:56.410
Right?

00:28:56.410 --> 00:28:58.720
So this is eight transactions
netted down to four.

00:28:58.720 --> 00:29:02.110
Usually this is millions
of transactions netted down

00:29:02.110 --> 00:29:06.420
to tens of thousands or maybe
millions of transactions

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:11.010
literally netted down to, if
there was 100 clearing members,

00:29:11.010 --> 00:29:13.200
it would be 100
transactions, because they'd

00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:21.750
each have one net transaction
per security, per security.

00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:24.000
And so you need to
keep the information

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.430
of the millions of
transactions to properly

00:29:26.430 --> 00:29:29.880
record for your
customers, for your taxes,

00:29:29.880 --> 00:29:33.210
for all sorts of other reasons.

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:36.270
But you've netted down
for counterparty reasons.

00:29:36.270 --> 00:29:39.270
Does that help?

00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:40.390
Question over here.

00:29:40.390 --> 00:29:40.890
Sean.

00:29:40.890 --> 00:29:43.145
AUDIENCE: I was just curious.

00:29:43.145 --> 00:29:45.220
It's very understandable
for equities.

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:47.796
But for principal
commodities, [? the full ?]

00:29:47.796 --> 00:29:52.060
commodity derivatives, for
instance in the clearing space,

00:29:52.060 --> 00:29:54.540
does it actually involve
the physical delivery

00:29:54.540 --> 00:29:59.700
of the netted
commodity [INAUDIBLE]??

00:29:59.700 --> 00:30:02.242
Because there's a different type
for delivery, and how that--

00:30:02.242 --> 00:30:02.950
GARY GENSLER: OK.

00:30:02.950 --> 00:30:04.590
So Sean's asked
the question, what

00:30:04.590 --> 00:30:06.660
if you're not dealing
with digitized assets,

00:30:06.660 --> 00:30:07.990
but physical assets?

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:08.490
I think.

00:30:08.490 --> 00:30:09.780
You used the word commodity.

00:30:09.780 --> 00:30:11.865
But I was presuming
you meant physical.

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:17.370
So some of the innovations
of the 19th century

00:30:17.370 --> 00:30:19.740
relate here when
they started to have

00:30:19.740 --> 00:30:22.770
standardized contracts
for commodities

00:30:22.770 --> 00:30:26.610
that were held in warehouses.

00:30:26.610 --> 00:30:31.550
In essence, to facilitate
some of this netting

00:30:31.550 --> 00:30:34.730
was also why central
warehouses, this clearing

00:30:34.730 --> 00:30:36.890
house in the middle in
physical commodities,

00:30:36.890 --> 00:30:40.310
could be a warehouse that held
the gold, held the silver,

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:42.830
held the corn or wheat.

00:30:42.830 --> 00:30:45.560
And if they're holding
that corn or wheat,

00:30:45.560 --> 00:30:48.230
they started to have
specifications as to what

00:30:48.230 --> 00:30:50.390
standards there were.

00:30:50.390 --> 00:30:52.850
In gold and silver,
it was percent.

00:30:52.850 --> 00:30:59.065
It was called the,
let's see, assay--

00:30:59.065 --> 00:31:00.440
I'm trying to
remember the word--

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:04.100
but what percent
gold or silver it is.

00:31:04.100 --> 00:31:07.070
But in corn and wheat,
there was a more detailed

00:31:07.070 --> 00:31:12.680
what's going into the warehouse
to commoditize it so that it

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.990
was a standard contract.

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:20.230
If it's truly physical and not
commodity, it's much harder.

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:26.290
Then you can't really net down
my house versus Shimon's house.

00:31:26.290 --> 00:31:28.905
They're two different houses.

00:31:28.905 --> 00:31:31.460
Does that help?

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:33.870
But literally by the
late 19th century,

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:37.200
even in the commodities
space running out of Chicago,

00:31:37.200 --> 00:31:39.140
they figured out
central clearing houses

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:43.610
with a lot of counterparty risk.

00:31:43.610 --> 00:31:45.560
So there's an economic
reason we have

00:31:45.560 --> 00:31:46.970
centralized clearing houses.

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:51.980
And the biggest economic
reason is netting.

00:31:51.980 --> 00:31:56.330
And netting lowers something
called counterparty risk.

00:31:56.330 --> 00:32:00.530
Instead of having literally
millions of transactions,

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:02.660
you'll have thousands.

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:04.398
And you'll have less
counterparty risk.

00:32:04.398 --> 00:32:05.690
It also lowers one other thing.

00:32:05.690 --> 00:32:07.130
So it lowers counterparty risk.

00:32:07.130 --> 00:32:09.130
And what is the other
thing you think it lowers?

00:32:09.130 --> 00:32:11.223
Anybody?

00:32:11.223 --> 00:32:12.390
AUDIENCE: Transactions cost.

00:32:12.390 --> 00:32:14.682
GARY GENSLER: Transactions
cost because it's efficient.

00:32:17.280 --> 00:32:20.850
We used to call it you take
a lot of lines off the page.

00:32:20.850 --> 00:32:23.520
So in the old human
days, you'd have

00:32:23.520 --> 00:32:28.390
to have fewer humans
actually pushing paper.

00:32:28.390 --> 00:32:29.650
Hugo.

00:32:29.650 --> 00:32:32.230
AUDIENCE: Another
clarification question.

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:35.650
So from the participants side,
so from a hedge fund side

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:39.615
or whatever or a
trading desk side,

00:32:39.615 --> 00:32:41.740
do they just go about their
day trading everything?

00:32:41.740 --> 00:32:44.183
And then the next day
the clearing house

00:32:44.183 --> 00:32:46.600
tells them, OK, you made all
these transactions yesterday.

00:32:46.600 --> 00:32:49.420
But we really only
need 35 [INAUDIBLE]..

00:32:49.420 --> 00:32:51.790
Or how does it [INAUDIBLE]?

00:32:51.790 --> 00:32:56.110
GARY GENSLER: In that
case, looking back to this,

00:32:56.110 --> 00:32:57.760
you are either the
buyer or seller.

00:32:57.760 --> 00:32:59.200
And you're dealing
with a broker.

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:03.713
So if you're a hedge
fund, you often

00:33:03.713 --> 00:33:05.380
enter into an arrangement
with a broker.

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:07.640
And it's called a prime
brokerage arrangement.

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:09.640
And you might have a prime
brokerage arrangement

00:33:09.640 --> 00:33:11.680
with more than one
Wall Street firm.

00:33:11.680 --> 00:33:14.580
But you rarely would have
it with more than three.

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:17.130
So even if I'm doing a
trade through Merrill Lynch,

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:18.900
if my prime brokerage
arrangement is

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:25.420
at Goldman Sachs, Merrill is
going to get a commission.

00:33:25.420 --> 00:33:27.970
But they're going to give up
my prime brokerage arrangements

00:33:27.970 --> 00:33:28.870
to Goldman Sachs.

00:33:28.870 --> 00:33:32.950
And that helps me, me the hedge
fund, get more netting as well.

00:33:32.950 --> 00:33:36.100
And that's a development
in the last 20 years,

00:33:36.100 --> 00:33:39.670
this concept of prime brokerage.

00:33:39.670 --> 00:33:41.260
But to answer your
question, yes.

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:42.370
I go about my business.

00:33:42.370 --> 00:33:43.560
I trade all day.

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:48.130
And unless I get a phone call
or an electronic communication

00:33:48.130 --> 00:33:51.870
from my prime brokerage
saying you've hit your lines,

00:33:51.870 --> 00:33:56.880
you do have credit limits and
position limits in essence.

00:33:56.880 --> 00:33:58.650
But your prime brokerage--

00:33:58.650 --> 00:34:01.650
and I might say, well, I
need something moved over.

00:34:01.650 --> 00:34:05.220
I need some more credit today.

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:05.862
But yes.

00:34:05.862 --> 00:34:08.070
You go about your business
until your prime brokerage

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:11.020
says slow down.

00:34:11.020 --> 00:34:11.520
Shimon?

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:13.690
AUDIENCE: But [INAUDIBLE]
question says that

00:34:13.690 --> 00:34:16.580
if you're a lot like LTCM--

00:34:16.580 --> 00:34:18.372
GARY GENSLER: Long-Term
Capital Management.

00:34:18.372 --> 00:34:20.622
AUDIENCE: --at some point,
they were running a balance

00:34:20.622 --> 00:34:22.230
sheet of a trillion dollars.

00:34:22.230 --> 00:34:24.409
And part of the reason
why, when bankrupt is they

00:34:24.409 --> 00:34:27.145
didn't want to use
one prime broker,

00:34:27.145 --> 00:34:29.270
because they don't want to
reveal all their trades.

00:34:29.270 --> 00:34:31.389
But then their prime
brokers could not

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:35.570
net out their positions, because
I may hold one leg with you

00:34:35.570 --> 00:34:38.739
and another leg with you.

00:34:38.739 --> 00:34:41.120
The net may be zero.

00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:43.429
But there's no way for
you to actually reconcile

00:34:43.429 --> 00:34:46.670
that or reconcile that risk.

00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:48.610
So it's a real problem.

00:34:48.610 --> 00:34:50.360
GARY GENSLER: Long-Term
Capital Management

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:55.250
was a hedge fund
operating in Connecticut.

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.590
It was founded in
the early 1990s

00:34:57.590 --> 00:34:59.790
by a man named John
Meriwether, who

00:34:59.790 --> 00:35:03.610
is a very famous trader
from Salomon Brothers

00:35:03.610 --> 00:35:05.300
and very successful.

00:35:05.300 --> 00:35:10.460
And then he started it with
some remarkable finance

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:14.060
faculty from here, at
MIT, and elsewhere--

00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:17.000
Bob Merton, who is
a Nobel laureate.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.220
Brilliant, brilliant
team of folks.

00:35:20.220 --> 00:35:22.940
But they ran into a little
challenge four years later.

00:35:22.940 --> 00:35:26.750
They had about $125 billion
balance sheet, $4 billion

00:35:26.750 --> 00:35:30.800
in capital, and 1.2
trillion in swaps.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:32.000
Why do I know the numbers?

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:34.880
I got the phone call with my
one-year-old sitting on my lap.

00:35:34.880 --> 00:35:36.620
And I picked up the phone.

00:35:36.620 --> 00:35:38.120
And I said, hello?

00:35:38.120 --> 00:35:40.790
And the voice on the other
line said, Treasury operator.

00:35:40.790 --> 00:35:42.830
I've got the Treasury
secretary for you.

00:35:42.830 --> 00:35:43.820
And I get on the phone.

00:35:43.820 --> 00:35:44.930
I go, yes, Bob?

00:35:44.930 --> 00:35:45.960
It was Bob Rubin.

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:47.210
It was the Treasury secretary.

00:35:47.210 --> 00:35:47.950
Bob, what's up?

00:35:47.950 --> 00:35:48.850
It was a Saturday.

00:35:48.850 --> 00:35:50.980
Isabel was on my lap.

00:35:50.980 --> 00:35:53.590
He says, do you know anything
about Long-Term Capital

00:35:53.590 --> 00:35:54.180
Management?

00:35:54.180 --> 00:35:56.050
He goes through
some of the figures.

00:35:56.050 --> 00:35:56.800
I'll never forget.

00:35:56.800 --> 00:35:59.020
He says, I hear from Alan--

00:35:59.020 --> 00:36:02.090
that would be Alan Greenspan,
who was the head of the Federal

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:02.620
Reserve--

00:36:02.620 --> 00:36:05.005
I hear from Alan that they
have over a trillion dollars

00:36:05.005 --> 00:36:06.710
of derivatives.

00:36:06.710 --> 00:36:08.470
That's Shimon's number.

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:10.357
He says, is that a big number?

00:36:10.357 --> 00:36:12.440
Well, you have to understand,
Bob's sense of humor

00:36:12.440 --> 00:36:17.410
was quite-- at that moment,
he knew it was a big number.

00:36:17.410 --> 00:36:19.990
So I flew up the next day.

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:22.630
And with somebody from
the Federal Reserve

00:36:22.630 --> 00:36:25.660
Bank in New York,
Peter Fisher, we

00:36:25.660 --> 00:36:27.880
sat around the
conference table looking

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:30.040
at these facts and figures.

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:33.850
And then I got back on the plane
and flew back to Washington

00:36:33.850 --> 00:36:34.840
to be with my family.

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:37.510
The next day was actually Rosh
Hashanah, the Jewish holiday.

00:36:37.510 --> 00:36:40.230
And I wasn't going to work.

00:36:40.230 --> 00:36:43.910
And I had to call Bob and
his deputy, Larry Summers,

00:36:43.910 --> 00:36:46.160
up and give them my feedback.

00:36:46.160 --> 00:36:49.040
And I said, this
thing's going down.

00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:52.100
Bear Stearns was
their prime brokerage.

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:55.010
And Bear Stearns, who 20
years later failed themselves,

00:36:55.010 --> 00:36:58.730
but Bear Stearns said, we're
pulling the prime brokerage

00:36:58.730 --> 00:37:01.460
account if you can't
post another half

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:04.015
a billion dollars by Wednesday.

00:37:04.015 --> 00:37:05.390
Well, there was
no way they could

00:37:05.390 --> 00:37:07.010
post another half
a billion dollars,

00:37:07.010 --> 00:37:08.840
because their $4
billion of capital

00:37:08.840 --> 00:37:11.210
we could best figure on
that Sunday was somewhere

00:37:11.210 --> 00:37:16.427
covering around 400 or 500
million at that point in time.

00:37:16.427 --> 00:37:18.010
Well, when you have
a lot of leverage,

00:37:18.010 --> 00:37:20.860
you have $1.2 trillion of
derivatives which are all

00:37:20.860 --> 00:37:22.690
sort of leveraged in
one way or another

00:37:22.690 --> 00:37:25.660
and you've got $125
billion balance sheet, even

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:29.870
with the best minds, the
best finance faculty--

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:32.160
and they really are
terrific individuals.

00:37:32.160 --> 00:37:35.440
And Meriwether was
quite a trader.

00:37:35.440 --> 00:37:38.390
Sometimes markets
go against you.

00:37:38.390 --> 00:37:42.210
Correlation risk, liquidity
risk, and so forth.

00:37:42.210 --> 00:37:47.090
So they pulled the plug
the next day, basically.

00:37:47.090 --> 00:37:49.850
That's the Long-Term Capital
Management story I remember.

00:37:49.850 --> 00:37:54.140
But it's just because I
kind of had to live it.

00:37:54.140 --> 00:37:57.620
