00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:05.960
and by its copies of
ledgers and reconciliation,

00:51:05.960 --> 00:51:10.100
has a lot of opportunity
for greater efficiency.

00:51:10.100 --> 00:51:12.620
And the question is whether
blockchain technology,

00:51:12.620 --> 00:51:17.260
maybe permissioned, can bring
some of that efficiency.

00:51:17.260 --> 00:51:18.480
That's the thought.

00:51:18.480 --> 00:51:20.272
And that's what the
chart was just trying--

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:25.490
by the way, the Congress
didn't agree with the Fed.

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:28.550
They left the authorities
at the SEC and CFTC.

00:51:28.550 --> 00:51:31.880
And those are for
stories other times.

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:34.580
I personally felt it could
be a shared authority.

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:36.650
And we ended up with
some shared authorities.

00:51:36.650 --> 00:51:41.010
But I thought that the CFTC
and SEC have domain knowledge.

00:51:41.010 --> 00:51:44.270
And it really important to keep
the SEC involved in securities

00:51:44.270 --> 00:51:48.260
clearing and the CFTC involved
in derivatives clearing

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:52.970
for that domain knowledge, but
that the Federal Reserve also

00:51:52.970 --> 00:51:55.700
came in under something called
Title VIII of Dodd-Frank.

00:51:55.700 --> 00:51:57.440
And they also got authorities.

00:51:57.440 --> 00:52:00.320
So we made it more complicated,
because now there's

00:52:00.320 --> 00:52:04.430
multiple dotted lines for this.

00:52:04.430 --> 00:52:08.060
The Federal Reserve basically
has an account with everybody.

00:52:08.060 --> 00:52:12.410
Or they have some
oversight of everybody.

00:52:12.410 --> 00:52:14.335
So then the question on
blockchain technology,

00:52:14.335 --> 00:52:16.460
could you take the clearing
house out of the middle

00:52:16.460 --> 00:52:18.470
and do the thing on the right?

00:52:18.470 --> 00:52:22.500
And my question for you all is,
do you think the economics--

00:52:22.500 --> 00:52:24.570
I'm not talking
about the technology.

00:52:24.570 --> 00:52:26.930
I'm not talking about
whether it's performance.

00:52:26.930 --> 00:52:29.540
If you wish, you can go five
or 10 years down the road

00:52:29.540 --> 00:52:32.660
and say it's got all this
scalability and performance.

00:52:32.660 --> 00:52:36.110
Do you think the technology,
without something

00:52:36.110 --> 00:52:40.250
in the middle, what's
the economics about that?

00:52:40.250 --> 00:52:42.200
Anybody?

00:52:42.200 --> 00:52:42.970
Eilon?

00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:45.880
AUDIENCE: I still want
to support the left side

00:52:45.880 --> 00:52:47.645
for liquid markets
because of the netting.

00:52:47.645 --> 00:52:49.020
GARY GENSLER:
Because of netting.

00:52:49.020 --> 00:52:49.603
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:54.180
I can't see a
blockchain solution

00:52:54.180 --> 00:52:56.850
working well when
you need netting

00:52:56.850 --> 00:53:00.720
to enjoy the efficiencies
of selling and shorting,

00:53:00.720 --> 00:53:01.580
shorting basically.

00:53:01.580 --> 00:53:02.372
GARY GENSLER: Yeah.

00:53:02.372 --> 00:53:05.580
But the question really
is, can you somehow,

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:10.090
on the right with
shared ledger, still

00:53:10.090 --> 00:53:12.410
get some benefit of netting?

00:53:12.410 --> 00:53:12.910
Right?

00:53:12.910 --> 00:53:14.950
You're saying you're
inclined here,

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:19.820
because you want to get the
netting for economic reasons.

00:53:19.820 --> 00:53:22.690
So as a ledger structure,
can you get the netting here?

00:53:22.690 --> 00:53:24.620
Shimon?

00:53:24.620 --> 00:53:26.120
AUDIENCE: You don't
need the netting

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:29.090
