00:53:47.480 --> 00:53:48.897
then you don't
care about netting.

00:53:48.897 --> 00:53:51.550
AUDIENCE: You care because you
face so many transaction fees.

00:53:51.550 --> 00:53:52.092
AUDIENCE: No.

00:53:52.092 --> 00:53:53.925
But that's going to be
a lot more efficient.

00:53:53.925 --> 00:54:00.570
So why-- again, do you think the
[? real ?] transaction fees are

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:02.300
a big economic issue here?

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:02.910
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:54:02.910 --> 00:54:03.930
That's what I think.

00:54:03.930 --> 00:54:06.040
GARY GENSLER: And I'm
sorry that you don't.

00:54:06.040 --> 00:54:07.220
AUDIENCE: So now it's fine.

00:54:07.220 --> 00:54:07.762
I don't know.

00:54:07.762 --> 00:54:08.726
I mean, I don't know.

00:54:08.726 --> 00:54:11.030
For really intense
help, how much

00:54:11.030 --> 00:54:15.050
do you pay per transaction with
the clearing house and without?

00:54:15.050 --> 00:54:18.950
Maybe the net will give you
only 10% of the transaction.

00:54:18.950 --> 00:54:21.230
But the cost of having
the clearing house

00:54:21.230 --> 00:54:22.903
is more than 10 times.

00:54:22.903 --> 00:54:23.570
AUDIENCE: Maybe.

00:54:23.570 --> 00:54:25.760
AUDIENCE: So the economics
depends on those numbers,

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:27.840
I think.

00:54:27.840 --> 00:54:30.570
GARY GENSLER: Is
that a question?

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:31.140
Hugo?

00:54:31.140 --> 00:54:32.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:54:32.130 --> 00:54:35.220
So you still can get
some of the netting.

00:54:35.220 --> 00:54:38.250
Let's just talk about blockchain
transactions on Bitcoin.

00:54:38.250 --> 00:54:40.110
You can batch transactions.

00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:42.960
So you can have multiple
inputs and multiple outputs.

00:54:42.960 --> 00:54:44.590
And that's kind of like netting.

00:54:44.590 --> 00:54:46.682
Then you have to
have a second system

00:54:46.682 --> 00:54:48.390
on top of that that
keeps track of what's

00:54:48.390 --> 00:54:49.557
going on throughout the day.

00:54:49.557 --> 00:54:52.430
And then it just
does the transactions

00:54:52.430 --> 00:54:56.070
on a daily basis or an
hourly basis or whatever.

00:54:56.070 --> 00:54:58.570
That takes care of that netting.

00:54:58.570 --> 00:54:59.160
Right?

00:54:59.160 --> 00:55:00.660
GARY GENSLER: So
Hugo contends maybe

00:55:00.660 --> 00:55:03.150
you can get this economic
thing called netting

00:55:03.150 --> 00:55:06.570
and still have a shared
distributed ledger.

00:55:06.570 --> 00:55:09.630
Or you could do it off chain.

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:12.900
I think, Shimon
to your question,

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:15.360
this is a big
economic thing either

00:55:15.360 --> 00:55:17.220
because we've just
grown accustomed to it

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:21.360
over a couple centuries or
it's fundamental to how markets

00:55:21.360 --> 00:55:25.460
trade, that we don't prefund.

00:55:25.460 --> 00:55:29.770
It's that economics that
blockchain technology

00:55:29.770 --> 00:55:31.690
will challenge.

00:55:31.690 --> 00:55:34.060
But we might stay with
a central clearing house

00:55:34.060 --> 00:55:35.770
if the economics are that value.

00:55:35.770 --> 00:55:40.900
Well, the economics of, in
essence, not prefunding,

00:55:40.900 --> 00:55:45.390
and thus, some
delayed settlement.

00:55:45.390 --> 00:55:48.210
Whereas in the past, we always
had delayed settlement at first

00:55:48.210 --> 00:55:50.100
because there was
so much paperwork.

00:55:50.100 --> 00:55:52.080
We had to have
delayed settlement.

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:53.700
We went digitized.

00:55:53.700 --> 00:55:59.480
And now, really in 2018, we
don't need delayed settlement

00:55:59.480 --> 00:56:03.130
or batch processing.

00:56:03.130 --> 00:56:05.010
So now you've
exposed, well, wait.

00:56:05.010 --> 00:56:07.670
What are the economics?

00:56:07.670 --> 00:56:08.765
Tom and then Alin?

00:56:08.765 --> 00:56:10.890
AUDIENCE: Could you still
have a delayed settlement

00:56:10.890 --> 00:56:14.290
with a blockchain system just
