They call a DAML, or Digital
Asset Machine Language?

00:56:47.585 --> 00:56:48.710
I don't know what the M is.

00:56:48.710 --> 00:56:51.606
But they call it DAML.

00:56:51.606 --> 00:56:52.797
Alin?

00:56:52.797 --> 00:56:53.380
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:56:53.380 --> 00:56:56.063
We've said you cannot
prefund on the right.

00:56:56.063 --> 00:56:56.730
Is that correct?

00:57:01.927 --> 00:57:04.260
GARY GENSLER: I think you
could through smart contracts.

00:57:04.260 --> 00:57:05.790
I think you could find this.

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:10.860
But the challenge with just
the picture, the picture

00:57:10.860 --> 00:57:13.110
suggests there's no
central counterparty

00:57:13.110 --> 00:57:15.720
to do all the netting.

00:57:15.720 --> 00:57:19.290
And so the question is, can
you have this ledger structure

00:57:19.290 --> 00:57:23.760
and still find a way to
net down all the positions?

00:57:23.760 --> 00:57:25.610
AUDIENCE: Well,
like Shimon said,

00:57:25.610 --> 00:57:28.140
there is no need for that.

00:57:28.140 --> 00:57:30.450
You get that implicitly
by recording everything

00:57:30.450 --> 00:57:31.672
and executing.

00:57:31.672 --> 00:57:33.755
GARY GENSLER: But if you're
recording-- all right.

00:57:33.755 --> 00:57:35.150
I'm agreeing with that, too.

00:57:35.150 --> 00:57:36.930
But that's where I
get to if you need

00:57:36.930 --> 00:57:42.360
to do Shimon's approach, which
is simultaneous execution

00:57:42.360 --> 00:57:45.180
and settlement, then
you need to prefund,

00:57:45.180 --> 00:57:47.550
even if that prefunding
is by nanoseconds.

00:57:47.550 --> 00:57:49.377
But you need to prefund.

00:57:49.377 --> 00:57:50.460
AUDIENCE: Not necessarily.

00:57:50.460 --> 00:57:52.430
You could, sort of
optimistically, you

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:55.895
could post a transaction that
says, I want to buy a stock.

00:57:55.895 --> 00:57:57.270
And I'm not going
to prove to you

00:57:57.270 --> 00:57:58.980
that I have money to buy it.

00:57:58.980 --> 00:58:01.900
You record it, if you were
saying optimistically.

00:58:01.900 --> 00:58:04.738
And later on--

00:58:04.738 --> 00:58:05.780
GARY GENSLER: It depends.

00:58:05.780 --> 00:58:10.200
The word record-- let me use
a different word, settle.

00:58:10.200 --> 00:58:13.470
Settlement means final
legal rights have moved

00:58:13.470 --> 00:58:16.380
from one party to another.

00:58:16.380 --> 00:58:18.770
So the word settlement
has a meaning that I just

00:58:18.770 --> 00:58:20.060
want to come back to.

00:58:20.060 --> 00:58:22.730
It means I'm
recording on a ledger

00:58:22.730 --> 00:58:25.070
that I no longer
have legal rights.

00:58:25.070 --> 00:58:26.890
So this alpha has
legal rights to it.

00:58:29.580 --> 00:58:32.080
And I think you would have
to prefund if you were

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:34.480
doing true settlement ledgers.

00:58:34.480 --> 00:58:36.100
AUDIENCE: Sure, sure.

00:58:36.100 --> 00:58:38.860
I guess I'm saying it seems like
you could simulate the clearing

00:58:38.860 --> 00:58:40.420
house.

00:58:40.420 --> 00:58:42.442
In the right side
of this picture,

00:58:42.442 --> 00:58:43.900
the clearing house
just distributed

00:58:43.900 --> 00:58:45.070
using the consensus protocol.

00:58:45.070 --> 00:58:45.940
GARY GENSLER: Right.

00:58:45.940 --> 00:58:48.593
I think you're right
that you could.

00:58:48.593 --> 00:58:50.260
But if you're going
all the way to where

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:54.590
Shimon is, like Bitcoin, and
you're doing final settlement,

00:58:54.590 --> 00:58:57.170
final settlement
recordation, then I

00:58:57.170 --> 00:58:59.257
think you have to prefund.

00:58:59.257 --> 00:59:00.590
A couple of questions over here.

00:59:00.590 --> 00:59:02.700
Eric, Ross.

00:59:02.700 --> 00:59:06.470
AUDIENCE: The reason that the
prefunding was [INAUDIBLE]

