and that 15 or 20 years from
now, every clearing house

01:03:08.390 --> 01:03:10.070
will be using what
they would consider

01:03:10.070 --> 01:03:12.320
a permissioned
blockchain solution,

01:03:12.320 --> 01:03:17.030
because it will so significantly
lower the back office

01:03:17.030 --> 01:03:20.000
costs for their
market participants

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:22.010
who are now holding records.

01:03:22.010 --> 01:03:27.620
Each bank, was it 77 members
from an earlier-- yeah.

01:03:27.620 --> 01:03:29.930
Each bank has to hold records.

01:03:29.930 --> 01:03:32.750
It could be held
in a shared ledger.

01:03:32.750 --> 01:03:35.240
And they would lower
the reconciliation cost.

01:03:35.240 --> 01:03:36.980
And they believe
the second advantage

01:03:36.980 --> 01:03:38.630
is using smart contracts.

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:41.570
Now, are they exactly
the smart contracts

01:03:41.570 --> 01:03:43.170
like on the Ethereum network?

01:03:43.170 --> 01:03:46.100
No, because they don't
have a native token.

01:03:46.100 --> 01:03:48.170
They don't have a DAP
and a native token.

01:03:48.170 --> 01:03:51.410
But it's still automating
certain processes,

01:03:51.410 --> 01:03:56.510
automating certain I'll call
it back office processes.

01:03:56.510 --> 01:03:58.130
So they're very committed to it.

01:03:58.130 --> 01:04:00.950
And they're going to
roll it out in 2020.

01:04:00.950 --> 01:04:05.210
And then, for 12 months,
run it simultaneous

01:04:05.210 --> 01:04:07.590
with their legacy system.

01:04:07.590 --> 01:04:13.980
So their cut over for
assuring that it's resilient

01:04:13.980 --> 01:04:16.650
is at 12 month test.

01:04:16.650 --> 01:04:18.510
Most major market
infrastructures

01:04:18.510 --> 01:04:21.850
that roll things out do not roll
simultaneously for 12 months.

01:04:21.850 --> 01:04:24.210
But they all roll simultaneous.

01:04:24.210 --> 01:04:28.380
Whether it's a month,
whether it's 90 days,

01:04:28.380 --> 01:04:31.200
you can't cut over the back
office of the New York Stock

01:04:31.200 --> 01:04:35.370
Exchange and just
test it for one day.

01:04:35.370 --> 01:04:36.490
Or you can.

01:04:36.490 --> 01:04:40.944
It's just kind of
choppy and a big risk.

01:04:40.944 --> 01:04:42.090
AUDIENCE: Quick question.

01:04:42.090 --> 01:04:45.285
Are they going to use a stable
coin to settle the transaction?

01:04:45.285 --> 01:04:47.160
How are they going to
settle the transaction?

01:04:47.160 --> 01:04:49.368
Because I can see how you
issue securities digitally.

01:04:49.368 --> 01:04:50.740
But you cannot issue cash.

01:04:50.740 --> 01:04:51.870
GARY GENSLER: So
this is very good.

01:04:51.870 --> 01:04:52.495
It's very good.

01:04:52.495 --> 01:04:56.940
So all of these
clearing houses, they

01:04:56.940 --> 01:05:00.840
are the final custodian
for the security.

01:05:00.840 --> 01:05:04.900
Securities are dematerialized,
meaning they're all digital.

01:05:04.900 --> 01:05:07.890
And so those digital
assets are held on a ledger

01:05:07.890 --> 01:05:10.710
and what's called
the golden record.

01:05:10.710 --> 01:05:13.320
This is the words used in
the securities business.

01:05:13.320 --> 01:05:16.140
The gold record or the
golden record, meaning it

01:05:16.140 --> 01:05:19.083
is the legal,
verifiable thing you

01:05:19.083 --> 01:05:20.250
can go to in a court of law.

01:05:20.250 --> 01:05:22.020
And it says, this
is who owns this.

01:05:22.020 --> 01:05:22.800
Alpha owns it.

01:05:22.800 --> 01:05:25.080
Not Hugo.

01:05:25.080 --> 01:05:26.790
Sorry.

01:05:26.790 --> 01:05:28.950
You're working with Goldman
Sachs, though, right?

01:05:31.770 --> 01:05:34.830
That golden record is
there for securities.

01:05:34.830 --> 01:05:36.915
Who has the golden
record for cash?

01:05:36.915 --> 01:05:38.040
AUDIENCE: The central bank?

01:05:38.040 --> 01:05:41.700
GARY GENSLER: The central
bank or the fractional banking

01:05:41.700 --> 01:05:44.400
system, their commercial
bank subledger.

01:05:47.370 --> 01:05:49.290
Clearing houses
around the globe would

01:05:49.290 --> 01:05:54.280
like to be able to have direct
access to central bank money.

01:05:54.280 --> 01:05:58.100
And they currently do not in
any of the major jurisdictions

01:05:58.100 --> 01:05:58.670
that I know.

01:05:58.670 --> 01:05:59.950
I think.

01:05:59.950 --> 01:06:04.790
So what Australia does now,
this is what they do now.

01:06:04.790 --> 01:06:06.800
They net everybody down.

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:08.120
They get to t plus two.

01:06:08.120 --> 01:06:09.380
They're on that second day.

01:06:09.380 --> 01:06:10.490
Everything's netted down.

01:06:10.490 --> 01:06:14.350
And they're about to do
the whole closing out.

01:06:14.350 --> 01:06:17.650
One second before they do
the security settlement,

01:06:17.650 --> 01:06:20.300
they do the cash settlement.

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:23.382
They call this Delivery
Versus Payment, DVP.

01:06:23.382 --> 01:06:24.590
But they're a clearing house.

01:06:24.590 --> 01:06:28.000
And they do not want to take
risk with the central bank.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:31.420
They take all the money
and settle all the cash

01:06:31.420 --> 01:06:35.170
with the Royal Bank of
Australia, RBA I guess.

01:06:35.170 --> 01:06:36.280
Do I have the right name?

01:06:36.280 --> 01:06:40.300
Or is it a different-- is RBA
one of the banks in Australia?

01:06:40.300 --> 01:06:42.310
But they settle all the cash.

01:06:42.310 --> 01:06:45.790
And just within a
second, they settle.

01:06:45.790 --> 01:06:47.230
We think of it as DVP.

01:06:47.230 --> 01:06:49.360
But it's actually
technically not.

01:06:49.360 --> 01:06:53.380
Inside their clearing
systems, they

01:06:53.380 --> 01:06:55.540
have a form of
Australian dollars

01:06:55.540 --> 01:07:02.590
that is effectively digitally,
in their system, digital money.

01:07:02.590 --> 01:07:04.090
In essence, what
they're doing is

01:07:04.090 --> 01:07:11.497
clearing their internal digital
money versus Royal Bank money.

01:07:11.497 --> 01:07:12.330
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:07:12.330 --> 01:07:13.520
GARY GENSLER: All right.

01:07:13.520 --> 01:07:14.750
Sorry.

