01:08:33.720 --> 01:08:36.590
Japan Exchange Group for
the Tokyo Stock Exchange

01:08:36.590 --> 01:08:37.850
has done some tests.

01:08:37.850 --> 01:08:38.852
They've written papers.

01:08:38.852 --> 01:08:40.310
They're sort of
interesting papers.

01:08:40.310 --> 01:08:43.729
The last one was
earlier this year.

01:08:43.729 --> 01:08:47.840
They're really trying it
just on post trade matching.

01:08:47.840 --> 01:08:50.810
One of the securities firms
in Japan, I can't remember,

01:08:50.810 --> 01:08:54.620
is really pressing the Tokyo
Stock Exchange to do this.

01:08:54.620 --> 01:08:58.600
So there's some local commercial
politics that are going on.

01:08:58.600 --> 01:09:01.430
I can't remember
which exchange is--

01:09:01.430 --> 01:09:02.149
not exchange.

01:09:02.149 --> 01:09:06.740
One of the brokerage houses
is pushing them to do it.

01:09:06.740 --> 01:09:08.310
All permissioned systems.

01:09:08.310 --> 01:09:12.960
No, to my knowledge,
permissionless systems.

01:09:12.960 --> 01:09:16.490
Let's talk about ISDA for
a few minutes, derivatives

01:09:16.490 --> 01:09:20.750
common domain model.

01:09:20.750 --> 01:09:24.560
One of my former commissioner's
colleagues, Scott O'Malia,

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:25.640
runs ISDA.

01:09:29.689 --> 01:09:32.479
That's a international
trade organization.

01:09:32.479 --> 01:09:37.520
It's largely, largely
dominated by the 16 big banks

01:09:37.520 --> 01:09:43.100
around the globe that
probably transact 98% or 99%

01:09:43.100 --> 01:09:46.550
of derivatives around the globe.

01:09:46.550 --> 01:09:50.359
And it was started in the
1980s to do all the forms,

01:09:50.359 --> 01:09:54.140
all the forms to enter into the
legal contractual obligations

01:09:54.140 --> 01:09:55.980
called swaps.

01:09:55.980 --> 01:09:59.760
And over the years,
it's transitioned.

01:09:59.760 --> 01:10:01.500
It's also an advocacy group.

01:10:01.500 --> 01:10:04.470
And it lobbies
various regulators

01:10:04.470 --> 01:10:06.840
in Europe and the US and Asia.

01:10:06.840 --> 01:10:08.970
But they've, a year or so
ago, said, wait a minute.

01:10:08.970 --> 01:10:14.900
We could take a lot of the back
office of swaps, particularly

01:10:14.900 --> 01:10:17.930
swaps that are not going
into clearing houses.

01:10:17.930 --> 01:10:20.840
So it's called the non-cleared
or uncleared swaps.

01:10:20.840 --> 01:10:24.320
And maybe we can
create smart contracts

01:10:24.320 --> 01:10:27.110
to automate a bunch
of contractual terms.

01:10:27.110 --> 01:10:28.860
So that's the
second bullet point.

01:10:28.860 --> 01:10:30.290
And they contracted out.

01:10:30.290 --> 01:10:32.480
They put out a
request for proposal,

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:34.700
basically, for
somebody to come up

01:10:34.700 --> 01:10:37.970
with machine readable
standard representation.

01:10:37.970 --> 01:10:41.300
Call it code, a
scripting language.

01:10:41.300 --> 01:10:43.220
I can't remember if it's--

01:10:43.220 --> 01:10:45.200
oh, it's written in JavaScript.

01:10:45.200 --> 01:10:47.651
So written in Java
and JavaScript,

01:10:47.651 --> 01:10:53.150
a standard machine readable
code of various events.

01:10:53.150 --> 01:10:57.830
If it's a 20-year swap that's
going to pay every quarter 80

01:10:57.830 --> 01:11:02.660
quarterly payments, each of
those quarterly payments,

01:11:02.660 --> 01:11:05.810
fixed versus floating
payments, is somehow

01:11:05.810 --> 01:11:08.290
put into machine readable code.

01:11:08.290 --> 01:11:11.570
And Scott and ISDA's
view was, if we

01:11:11.570 --> 01:11:16.010
could get a broad consensus and
publish that machine readable

01:11:16.010 --> 01:11:19.400
code that everybody agrees on,
maybe that machine readable

01:11:19.400 --> 01:11:23.390
code could take the
place of legal contracts.

01:11:23.390 --> 01:11:27.150
ISDA, for 30 plus years, one
of their lines of business

01:11:27.150 --> 01:11:30.590
is creating those
legal contracts.

01:11:30.590 --> 01:11:32.990
Maybe we can get a
step ahead of this

01:11:32.990 --> 01:11:38.170
and get consensus amongst
these 16 big banks.

01:11:38.170 --> 01:11:41.240
There's about 100,000
users of swaps

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:42.830
when you say all the customers.

01:11:42.830 --> 01:11:45.870
It's not measured in
the tens of millions.

01:11:45.870 --> 01:11:47.990
I doubt anybody in
this room personally

01:11:47.990 --> 01:11:50.870
has a 20-year or 10-year swap.

01:11:50.870 --> 01:11:52.430
But I don't want to embarrass.

01:11:52.430 --> 01:11:54.920
Maybe somebody does.

01:11:54.920 --> 01:11:59.440
But it's an institutional
product, largely.

01:11:59.440 --> 01:12:00.850
That's their product.

01:12:00.850 --> 01:12:03.880
And it covers new
transactions, rate resets,

01:12:03.880 --> 01:12:08.930
partial terminations,
as I listed up there.

01:12:08.930 --> 01:12:10.510
Questions?

01:12:10.510 --> 01:12:15.380
And it's definitely very
much inspired by Ethereum

01:12:15.380 --> 01:12:19.260
and smart contracts and DAPs.

01:12:19.260 --> 01:12:24.360
But in essence, it's not
really blockchain technology.

01:12:24.360 --> 01:12:26.370
It's inspired by it, in a sense.

01:12:26.370 --> 01:12:30.060
AUDIENCE: They're just rewriting
the contracts instead of--

01:12:30.060 --> 01:12:33.410
they think they can have more
specificity and certainty

01:12:33.410 --> 01:12:37.020
of about what the contract
means by writing it in contract.

01:12:37.020 --> 01:12:40.570
GARY GENSLER: And importantly,
importantly, efficiency--

01:12:40.570 --> 01:12:44.530
to automate that which
humans are still doing, even

01:12:44.530 --> 01:12:46.900
if it's in written contract.

01:12:46.900 --> 01:12:49.130
So it's also automation
that's inspiring them.

01:12:52.413 --> 01:12:53.580
But you're absolutely right.

01:12:53.580 --> 01:12:57.030
It's taking legal contract,
getting into machine readable

01:12:57.030 --> 01:13:01.320
JavaScript code, getting
consensus on what that code is,

01:13:01.320 --> 01:13:04.008
getting some courts
to recognize it.

01:13:04.008 --> 01:13:05.550
And then you won't
even need to write

01:13:05.550 --> 01:13:09.510
some of this, a rate reset
or a partial termination,

01:13:09.510 --> 01:13:11.130
into the contract.

01:13:11.130 --> 01:13:15.470
You'd be referencing this.

01:13:15.470 --> 01:13:17.780
The longer term
objective is to say maybe

01:13:17.780 --> 01:13:23.623
we can put even more
of it right into code.

01:13:23.623 --> 01:13:26.040
AUDIENCE: People would have
to pool their money somewhere.

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:27.290
It's like we were
talking about, right?

01:13:27.290 --> 01:13:27.760
GARY GENSLER: That's correct.

01:13:27.760 --> 01:13:29.320
AUDIENCE: It's going
to execute itself,

01:13:29.320 --> 01:13:31.612
which is going to have to be
a pool of money somewhere.

01:13:31.612 --> 01:13:34.580
GARY GENSLER: That you might
have to some prefund or self

01:13:34.580 --> 01:13:36.410
fund or something.

01:13:36.410 --> 01:13:38.650
Let me go back
here, and then up.

01:13:38.650 --> 01:13:42.450
AUDIENCE: If they're using
blockchain on it, it can't be--

01:13:42.450 --> 01:13:44.450
GARY GENSLER: They call
it a blockchain project.

01:13:44.450 --> 01:13:46.620
But it's a--

01:13:46.620 --> 01:13:49.430
I think I've tried to
capture the essence of what

01:13:49.430 --> 01:13:50.580
I think they have here.

01:13:50.580 --> 01:13:52.250
It's definitely
blockchain inspired.

01:13:52.250 --> 01:13:54.520
I'm just not sure it's really
stored on a blockchain.

01:13:54.520 --> 01:13:55.145
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:13:55.145 --> 01:13:58.030
Because if you look at
credit default swap,

01:13:58.030 --> 01:14:00.515
you have to reference a credit
rating somewhere digitally.

01:14:00.515 --> 01:14:03.470
And wherever that's referenced
digitally, if someone makes

01:14:03.470 --> 01:14:05.990
a mistake, does a
transaction period that's

01:14:05.990 --> 01:14:07.945
based on that mistake
and it's fixed,

01:14:07.945 --> 01:14:09.820
someone's going to have
to be able to reverse

01:14:09.820 --> 01:14:11.245
that transaction.

01:14:11.245 --> 01:14:12.620
GARY GENSLER: So
what's raised is

01:14:12.620 --> 01:14:16.760
what about if it's referencing
some oracle, referencing

01:14:16.760 --> 01:14:19.640
some price source,
and there's an error.

01:14:19.640 --> 01:14:21.440
I believe, as I
understand it, they're

01:14:21.440 --> 01:14:24.300
writing some of that
into the code as well.

01:14:24.300 --> 01:14:26.630
So if it's referencing a
price off the New York Stock

01:14:26.630 --> 01:14:30.080
Exchange, how it does
that, what open API

01:14:30.080 --> 01:14:34.190
it references, how it pulls it.

01:14:34.190 --> 01:14:38.240
And they're trying
to say, let's make

01:14:38.240 --> 01:14:40.253
sure that it's what's
really verifiable.

01:14:40.253 --> 01:14:42.170
There's one more slide
on this that will help.

01:14:42.170 --> 01:14:43.220
This is their steps.

01:14:43.220 --> 01:14:47.000
This is their publicly
disclosed five steps.

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:48.560
This was in an October paper.

01:14:48.560 --> 01:14:50.930
It wasn't part of your reading.

01:14:50.930 --> 01:14:53.330
But select the parts of
derivatives contracts first.

01:14:53.330 --> 01:14:54.622
Automation would be worthwhile.

01:14:54.622 --> 01:14:55.372
They're effective.

01:14:55.372 --> 01:14:56.000
It's efficient.

01:14:56.000 --> 01:14:58.170
Let's find something
we can automate.

01:14:58.170 --> 01:15:00.980
Ross, that's their key driver.

01:15:00.980 --> 01:15:06.680
Then try to express it the legal
terms in a more formalized way.

01:15:06.680 --> 01:15:09.870
Get some standardization
about the law.

01:15:09.870 --> 01:15:12.370
Get that be represented
as functions,

01:15:12.370 --> 01:15:14.860
meaning computer code.

01:15:14.860 --> 01:15:16.620
So where can we be
efficient and automate?

01:15:16.620 --> 01:15:18.300
Where can we take
the legal words

01:15:18.300 --> 01:15:21.240
and get agreement,
put it into code,

01:15:21.240 --> 01:15:23.130
combine that into templates?

01:15:23.130 --> 01:15:26.430
I think some of this
is referencing oracles.

01:15:26.430 --> 01:15:29.100
And then validate that
the templates actually

01:15:29.100 --> 01:15:32.400
work and, ultimately, even
get some courts of law

01:15:32.400 --> 01:15:33.960
to accept them.

01:15:33.960 --> 01:15:35.670
That's their game plan.

01:15:40.829 --> 01:15:41.407
Shimon?

01:15:41.407 --> 01:15:43.490
AUDIENCE: I was thinking
